2. More particularly put them in mind that in Baptiſm a ſolemn profeſſion is made of belief in the Bleſſed Trinity: that is of God, in Three Perſons, Father, Son, and Holy Ghoſt: Unto whoſe Service we are there devoted. For it is no frivilous obſervation of Theophylact upon thoſe Words of our Saviour, XXVIII Mat. 19. Go and teach all Nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghoſt, That 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 ;
he does not ſay, Baptiſe them into the Names, but into the Name of the Father, Son, and Holy Ghoſt. For though they be three, yet their Name, viz.
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , Their Godhead is but one, as he there explains it. One God in three Perſons, of whoſe Love and Favour we are aſſured in Baptiſm: and ſhould value it above all the Riches in the World.
